2026-03-09 18:36:17,670 - OpenAILLM - INFO - Content: {"thought":"We have experiment results for 3 sets of (gamma, T, M) giving sound speeds.\nWe can hypothesize the law is similar to ideal gas speed of sound: v = sqrt(gamma * R * T / M), where R is universal gas constant (~8.314).\nLet's test:\n1) For first point: gamma=1.4,T=300,M=0.028 => sqrt(1.4*8.314*300/0.028) = sqrt(1.4*2494.2/0.028) => sqrt(1.4*89007.14) = sqrt(124609.996) ≈ 353.0. Our measured is ~39776? Wait big difference. Actually measured outputs are ~4e4, maybe units different: M maybe in kg/mol and T huge? No T here is ~300. That yields v in m/s normally ~350 m/s, not 40k m/s. That suggests factor ~100 scaling.\nLet's divide measured v² by (gamma*T/M):\nfor point1: v²=1.582...e9, (gamma*T/M) ≈ 15000; ratio ≈ 105,480.\nPoint2: v²=3.6686e10, ratio = (gamma*T/M) ≈ 208750 => 175,640.\nRatios not equal, so not exact simple form.\nLet's fit form v² = const * gamma * T / M: k1 = v1² * M / (gamma*T) etc.\nCompute k: point1: 1.582e9*0.028/(1.4*300) ≈ 105333. Point2: (3.6686e10*0.004)/(1.67*500) ≈ 175,634. Hmm not equal => maybe v = const * sqrt(gamma^a * T^b / M^c)\nWe can solve log-linear regression.\nLet's extract logs:\nlog v = a log gamma + b log T + c log M + log k\nMake 3 eqs for 3 points to solve.\nEquation1: log(39776.8777)=~10.591, logγ=0.3365, logT=5.7038, logM=-3.5756\nEq2: log(191567.8731)=~12.163, logγ=0.513, logT=6.2146, logM=-5.5215\nEq3: log(29878.6609)=~10.305, logγ=0.262, logT=5.5215, logM=-3.4420\nSystem: [0.3365 a + 5.7038 b -3.5756 c] + logk =10.591 etc.\nWe can solve but maybe easier to run one more experiment for better determination."}
